<h3>Bind Affinity</h3>

<p>You can now change your bind point (or the bind point of others).&nbsp; You
can bind yourself almost anywhere, but you can only bind others in city zones or
special areas designated for binding.&nbsp; When you gate or die, you will
return to the point you last bound your affinity.&nbsp; You can check your
current bind point with the &quot;/char info&quot; command.</p>

<h3>Burnout</h3>

<p>
With this spell, you can increase your pet's strength, AC and attack speed
(haste). You should always keep this buff on your pet as it insures your pet
will do more damage and take less damage. You can only cast Burnout on your pet
and only you can cast Burnout on your pet. The spell stacks with other haste
effects and spells. However, there is likely an undisclosed maximum haste effect
for pets. At this level you don't have to worry about hitting the maximum. Just
keep this buff on your pet. You will get a yellow message when the spell wears
off the pet.</p>

<p><i>
Historical Note: The spell name no longer fits the description. Burnout is so
named because the spell used to be a DOT on your pet. Literally, the pet would
burn itself out - sacrificing its health to do more damage. With the damage they
did to pets, they weren't often used spells. Now, there is no tradeoff except
the cost of mana to cast.</i></p>

<h3>Anti-Summoned Direct Damage</h3>

<p>Ward Summoned is a direct damage spell that works only on summoned
beings.&nbsp; It is more efficient than normal DD spells...and seems to be much
less resistible</p>

<h3>Rain Spells</h3>

<p>
Today's forecast? A front of raining swords is moving in from the west… This
spell does up to 3 waves of damage to the target and anything around it. Each
mob in the area of effect gets a chance to resist each wave. If one mob is in
the area of effect, it will get hit up to 3 times. If more mobs are in the area,
the number of waves is reduced. This can be a very mana efficient series of
spells. It can also be very disappointing to see all 3 waves get resisted. I'd
suggest using it at this level, although you won't find it all that useful until
you can debuff mob resists at level 24.</p>

<p>
If the mob leaves the area of effect before all waves have fallen, the wave just
&quot;missed&quot; the mob. Knowing that, you should not cast the spell too
early in the fight. Give the mob time to build up a little hatred of your pet or
tank. If the mob comes running for you when the first wave hits, you'll have
just wasted mana - and your tank isn't that effective if he's chasing a mob
that's chasing you.</p>

<p>
Don't stand in the area of effect. Also, if you're on a PVP server, the area is
subject to the rules of the server's engagement. You will hit anything in the
area you are allowed to hit.</p>

<p><i>
Historical Note: Pets used to count as a mob in terms of the number of waves of
damage. Although on blue servers your pet took no damage, it reduced the
efficiency enough to make the spell worthless. This has been fixed for some
time, although some websites still state that pets reduce the efficiency of
rain. That is no longer true.</i></p>

<h3>Column of Fire</h3>

<p>This is the only level you'll gain this type of spell.&nbsp; Consider this
spell a targetable version of Fire Flux.&nbsp; It will damage the target and everything around it.&nbsp; To use it, target
it and cast.&nbsp; If you can, you will damage the target and everything around
it in a single hit.&nbsp; In PVP, you need to be concerned for others in the
area (or maybe they're your target).&nbsp; On normal servers, you can target a
group member and cast.&nbsp; All mobs around that player will take damage, but
the player will not.&nbsp;
Be sure you are never in the area of effect as you'll take damage as well.</p>

<h3>Cancel Magic</h3>

<p>This spell will attempt remove one magical effect currently on the
target.&nbsp; Note that the magical effect you're trying to remove must be a
spell (not an inherent ability of the mob) -- even so, it may fail.&nbsp;
It is considered a hostile spell.&nbsp; Don't cast it unless you want to fight
the target.&nbsp; Also, if you're grouped with a debuff/DOT casting class, be
careful.&nbsp; Cancel magic attempts to remove the first spell on the mob.&nbsp;
If that is a magic-based spell cast by your group, you may be helping the mob by
removing it.&nbsp; (Some debuffs check against disease or poison and cannot be
removed by Cancel Magic).</p>

<p>Cancel magic has a beneficial use as well.&nbsp; If a player in your group is
hit with a magic-based debuff or DOT, you can remove it by casting cancel magic
on the player.&nbsp; Note that this spell removes all magical effects in the
order they are displayed in the buff box.&nbsp; So, if your group mate has a
shield and then the DOT, you will have to cast cancel magic twice: Once to
remove the shield and again to remove the DOT.&nbsp; Again, only magic-based
DOTs can be removed.&nbsp; Disease and Poison DOTs and debuffs require cures
that magicians cannot cast.</p>

<p><i>Historical Note:&nbsp; Cancel magic wasn't always a hostile spell.&nbsp;
You could strip the buffs off of a mob and it would just stand there.&nbsp; In
most cases the mob would rebuff itself if it could.&nbsp; Mobs got smart and
figured out that players canceling their buffs attacked them 99.8% of the time
(0.2% went link dead).</i></p>

<h3>Slot 1 Trick</h3>

<p>As mentioned above, Cancel Magic removes buffs, DOTs and debuffs in a
specific order.&nbsp; If you know you will be fighting monsters that cast
magic-based spells, it's a good idea to make sure that the first buff slot is
open.&nbsp; That way, you can cancel the DOT without stripping other beneficial
spells.&nbsp; To do this, have the player look at the buff in slot 1 and
remember what it is.&nbsp; (Right click it).&nbsp; The player should then
remove the buff by left-clicking it.&nbsp;&nbsp; Cast a buff that isn't needed
on the player.&nbsp; Invisibility is your only real choice at this level.&nbsp;
At level 16, See Invisible is a better choice.&nbsp; This spell will take the
first position, since it was open.</p>

<p>Rebuff the player with the spell that was originally in slot 1.&nbsp; Have
the player click to remove the &quot;junk&quot; slot 1 buff.&nbsp; You're good
to go!&nbsp; As long as slot 1 stays open, any DOT will fill that slot and you
can Cancel Magic to remove it without affecting other buffs.</p>

<h3>New Focus Item</h3>

<p>Summon Tarnished Bauble - when worn, this item will reduce the mana cost of
detrimental spells by 15%.&nbsp; The effect is limited to spells of the 24th
level or below.</p>

<h3>New Summoned Items</h3>

<p>Elemental Defender - this item is a shield that can also be worn in the back
slot by some classes.&nbsp; It increases AC and resists.&nbsp; Your pet will
benefit from this item.&nbsp; Simply give it to your pet and have faith that he
knows what to do with it.</p>

<h3>New Pet Skill</h3>

<p>Your pet's bare-handed attacks are now magical.</p>
